<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the FOUR `sys_choice` rows
    that enumerate the legal values of the `type` Choice field on the
    `x_[scope]_case_task` custom table inside the scoped application
    `x_[scope]_case_management`.

    Per AAP Section 0.5.7 (Data-Model Mapping verbatim) for x_[scope]_case_task:

        Field    Type     Constraints
        type     Choice   Investigation, Review, Follow-up, Other

    Per AAP Section 0.4.1 (Refactored Structure Planning):
        choices/sys_choice_case_task_type.xml -> Investigation, Review,
                                                 Follow-up, Other

    The values authored here are the EXHAUSTIVE, CLOSED enumeration that the
    AAP mandates - exactly four records, no more and no fewer. Per the
    MINIMAL CHANGE CLAUSE in AAP Section 0.7.2, additional task types such
    as `Audit`, `Triage`, `Approval`, `Notification`, `Escalation`, etc.
    are explicitly out of scope for this POC. ArkCase's `AcmTask.java`
    domain object carried a free-form `String type` field with no platform-
    level enumeration check (see Source-side reference below); the POC
    target collapses that unconstrained string into these four controlled
    Title Case labels through the parent dictionary entry's
    `<choice>3</choice>` setting plus the four sibling sys_choice records
    declared below.

    Per AAP Sections 0.5.2, 0.4.1, and 0.5.7, the labels declared here are
    read by:

      The parent dictionary entry that declares this field as Choice:
        ../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_task_type.xml
            (mandatory=true, choice=3 means "Choice list - dropdown only";
            because the field is mandatory, "Other" exists as a fallback
            bucket so a user can always file a task whose category does
            not fit Investigation, Review, or Follow-up without leaving
            the type field empty and tripping the form-level mandatory
            validation gate)

      Synthetic demo task seed records satisfying AAP Section 0.4.1
      minimum-data threshold ("at least one open and one closed task per
      demo case in `In Progress` or `Pending` state, to exercise the
      all-tasks-closed gate"):
        ../seed-data/tasks/x_[scope]_case_task_demo_*.xml
            (each demo task picks one of the four Title Case labels
            below by string-equality value - mixing all four categories
            across the demo task population so the dropdown rendering
            and the future "tasks by type" reports both have meaningful
            data on a fresh PDI re-import)

      The idempotent server-side seed script:
        ../scripts/seed_demo_data.js
            (writes synthetic task type labels via
            GlideRecord.setValue('type', 'Investigation' | 'Review' |
            'Follow-up' | 'Other'); the script-side string literals
            byte-match the labels declared here, so any drift between
            this Choice list and the seed script will leave the demo
            task `type` column blank on the seeded rows because
            ServiceNow rejects unknown choice values for dictionary
            entries declared with `<choice>3</choice>`.)

    Unlike the sibling ../choices/sys_choice_case_task_status.xml file,
    these four `type` values do NOT participate in any state-machine guard,
    transition validator, or blocking-error message on the case form.
    Per AAP Section 0.5.5, the case-resolution gate (the "All tasks must
    be closed before resolving this case." blocking error per AAP
    Section 0.7.4 verbatim) checks ONLY the task `status` field, not the
    `type` field. Task type is purely categorical metadata used for
    reporting and human filtering; choosing any of the four values
    (or transitioning between them, which the form actually permits
    via standard ServiceNow Choice-field semantics) does NOT alter the
    parent case's state-machine eligibility, the ACL evaluation, or the
    Resolved-transition gate.

    Semantic source-side reference (read-only, NOT byte-for-byte ported):
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-task-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/task/model/AcmTask.java line 85:
            private String type;
        ArkCase's task `type` was a free-form String field on the
        AcmTask domain object. The field carried NO Bean Validation
        constraints (no @Size, no @NotNull, no @Pattern), so any
        caller could assign any string. ArkCase's task-type vocabulary
        was distributed across BPMN process variables and ad-hoc
        Activiti taskDefinitionKey values; common observed labels in
        the legacy code base included free-form review-flow names,
        adhoc task descriptors, and engine-internal identifiers - none
        of which were enforceable at the JPA layer. The ServiceNow
        target replaces this fragmented free-form String with a
        controlled Choice vocabulary of four labels (Investigation,
        Review, Follow-up, Other) through the parent dictionary entry's
        `<choice>3</choice>` setting plus the sibling sys_choice
        records below. AAP Section 0.1.2 codifies this kind of
        free-form-String -> Choice tightening as the ServiceNow-side
        equivalent of ArkCase's bean-validation enforcement.
      - The four AAP-mandated values represent typical case-management
        task categories:
            Investigation - fact-finding, evidence-gathering work
            Review        - examination of submitted material or
                            decisions made by another party
            Follow-up     - additional contact or work flowing from
                            an earlier action
            Other         - fallback bucket for tasks that do not fit
                            any of the more specific categories;
                            without this fallback, the mandatory
                            `type` field would block creation of any
                            task whose category was not one of the
                            three more specific labels
        These four values are entirely defined by the AAP (Section
        0.5.7), not derived from any specific ArkCase source code.

    Constraints honored (AAP Sections 0.7.1, 0.7.2, 0.7.4):
      - EXACTLY four records: no fewer, no more. Per AAP Section 0.5.7
        verbatim. The four records below are the COMPLETE enumeration
        for this POC. The "extensible" annotation that appears next to
        the case `type` field in the AAP is NOT repeated for case_task
        `type` - this Choice list is treated as closed by the POC
        scope.
      - Title Case labels: `Investigation`, `Review`, `Follow-up`,
        `Other`. NOT all-uppercase (which ArkCase's BPMN engine commonly
        used: INVESTIGATION, REVIEW), NOT all-lowercase, NOT camelCase.
        The agent prompt explicitly warns that `Follow-up` MUST contain
        a single ASCII hyphen-minus character (U+002D) - NOT
        `Follow up` (with space), NOT `Followup` (no separator), NOT
        `Follow_up` (snake_case underscore), NOT `Follow-Up` (Title-
        cased after the hyphen), NOT en-dash, em-dash, or any other
        Unicode dash. The hyphen below is the same ASCII byte 0x2D
        used universally in plaintext writing.
      - Label = Value pattern: each `<value>` matches its sibling
        `<label>` byte-for-byte. The stored value IS the human-
        readable label - no integer state codes, no enum ordinals,
        no separate machine-key. This matches the pattern used by
        every other sibling Choice list in this app (case.type,
        case.status, case.priority, case.pending_reason, case_task.
        status, case_party.party_type) and lets reports group by the
        label without per-table lookup tables.
      - Sequence ordering aligned with the AAP-listed order in
        increments of 100:
            Investigation (100) -> Review (200) -> Follow-up (300)
                                -> Other (400)
        This drives:
            (a) the dropdown order on the case_task form (Investigation
                appears first because it is the most common task
                category in case-management workflows; Other appears
                last because it is the fallback)
            (b) the slice/bar order on any future task-type reports
            (c) the future extensibility - increment-of-100 spacing
                leaves room for inserting new types without
                renumbering (e.g., a hypothetical `Audit` could slot
                at sequence 150 between Investigation and Review),
                though the AAP MINIMAL CHANGE CLAUSE prohibits adding
                any in this POC build.
      - All four records are <inactive>false</inactive>: every value
        is active and selectable in the dropdown. There are no
        deprecated legacy values to filter out (this is a greenfield
        Choice list).
      - No <dependent_value/>: type is a TOP-LEVEL categorical
        indicator whose legal values do NOT depend on the parent case's
        type, on `status`, on `assigned_to`, or on any other field.
        The dependent_value mechanism is for declarative cascading
        choices at the form-rendering level only and is not used here
        because all four task types are valid on every case_task row
        regardless of context.
      - No <hint/>: the labels are self-documenting. The agent prompt
        explicitly suppresses helper text per the POC scope. Future
        builds may add hint text such as "Use 'Other' when the task
        does not fit a more specific category" if user feedback
        warrants it.
      - Scope-namespace exclusivity: every record's `<sys_scope>` and
        `<sys_package>` resolve into the `x_[scope]_case_management`
        scoped application by `source` attribute lookup. NO global-
        scope writes - the OOB tables sys_user, sys_user_group,
        sys_user_role, core_company, task, incident, etc. are never
        modified by these records.
      - Zero hardcoded cross-reference sys_ids: the `<sys_scope>` and
        `<sys_package>` text-node values resolve by scope source name
        (`x_[scope]_case_management`), not by literal sys_id. Each
        record's `<sys_id>` element value is THIS record's own
        deterministic primary key - computed as MD5 of the canonical
        identifier `x_[scope]_case_task.type.<Value>` so that
        re-generation of this XML yields byte-identical output (no
        random UUIDs). This is the same derivation pattern used by
        the sibling ../choices/sys_choice_case_task_status.xml file
        and ../choices/sys_choice_case_status.xml file. The sys_id
        is NOT a reference to any other record - it is this record's
        OWN identity, which the no-hardcoded-sys_id rule (AAP Section
        0.7.2) explicitly permits.
      - The literal `[scope]` placeholder is preserved per AAP
        convention; the PDI auto-assigns the actual scope id at App
        Engine Studio creation time, which the import process resolves
        into the final scope namespace.
      - English language only: `<language>en</language>` on every
        record per the POC scope. The platform supports localization
        via additional sys_choice records keyed by `language`, but
        no non-English locales are in scope.
      - `<sys_domain>global</sys_domain>` on every record: domain
        separation is not used by this scoped application.
      - No PII: the labels are categorical task-type terms only; no
        real names, email addresses, organizational identifiers, or
        case-content phrases are derived from or stored in these
        records.

    Cross-references (AAP Section 0.5.2 dependency ordering):
      THIS RECORD SET MUST LOAD AFTER:
        - ../app/sys_app/x_[scope]_case_management.xml (scoped application
          record; the sys_package source target)
        - ../app/sys_scope/x_[scope].xml (scope record; the sys_scope
          target)
        - ../tables/x_[scope]_case_task.xml (parent table; the type
          field's host)
        - ../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_task_type.xml (parent dictionary
          entry; declares the column shape, choice=3, mandatory=true.
          Without this entry the four sys_choice records below have no
          column to attach to; per AAP Section 0.5.2 "Choices after
          their parent dictionary entry", the dictionary entry MUST
          load first.)

      THIS RECORD SET MUST LOAD BEFORE all consumers enumerated above
      (demo task seed records and the seed_demo_data.js script).
      Loading order is enforced by the alphabetical Update Set preview
      ordering plus the record-by-record dependency-resolution pass.

    Source for the deterministic sys_id derivations:
        echo -n "x_[scope]_case_task.type.Investigation" | md5sum
            => c509a1c2ee11b17bb33984334f603baf
        echo -n "x_[scope]_case_task.type.Review"        | md5sum
            => b0337f92dc4ec6a9eb8e5a3e4faeccaf
        echo -n "x_[scope]_case_task.type.Follow-up"     | md5sum
            => 13e5648ac5e3de04d88ab1aef64f0165
        echo -n "x_[scope]_case_task.type.Other"         | md5sum
            => 2edff77acab5fc790a92ad36e2772600

    The MD5 input is the canonical identifier <table>.<element>.<value>,
    matching the same derivation pattern used by the sibling
    ../choices/sys_choice_case_task_status.xml file. The MD5 derivation
    guarantees that re-generation of this Update Set on any agent run
    produces byte-identical sys_ids (no random UUIDs), which is required
    for clean Update-Set re-import on a fresh PDI without creating
    duplicate sys_choice rows.
-->
<unload unload_date="2025-01-01 00:00:00">
